<br>
Fizzlethorpe was more along the middle of agreeances. He felt as though a full scale assault would prove effective but it would have to be planned to perfection in order to be successful. He had been watching the mortals of Antonica and saw how effectively they could raid many of the most valuable treasures with planning and coordination. Silently he watched as Lady Vox had fallen, and again peering from the shadows had watched Lord Nagafen meet the same fate. Granted these were not 2 of Veeshans more powerful children but he could see the promise.<br>
<br>
&quot;Might I suggest a compromise of sorts in regards to the plans of attack on the table?,&quot; he spoke. The collective council turned to him, shocked at the fact that he had finally spoken. &quot; I have watched the mortals achieve victory over Veeshans broodlings Vox and Naggy with a mixture of whats been proposed.&quot;.<br>
<br>
They turned full attention to him, weary of his suggestion, for how could soemthing worked out by mortals succeeed at a level that took the might of the gods and their children. The mumblings of Cazic and Innoruk mingled with that of Brell and Tunare. Neither was really willing to conceed that they would have to each have input in order to achieve victory.<br>
<br>
&quot;How can we learn from mortals,?&quot; the last word sounding like a bad taste in Cazics mouth. &quot;We created them in one way or another, how can they be able to plan victory for soemthing we have long sought ourselves?&quot; The others chimed in in agreeance.<br>
<br>
Fizzlethorpe sighed and began to explain. &quot; Im not saying that they have planned our attack, but they have divised a system of sorts that allows them to gain victory over advisaries far greater than themselves. It does come with cost, and there are those that will fall but after all this is goibng to be a war and all wars yeild their share of death.&quot; He went into deep explanation about the organization of waves and strategy he had witnessed.<br>
<br>
&quot;That sounds good in theory and all but how are we supposed to know how to plan this to perfection seeing as how we have never had to do this before?&quot; Brell did have a point. Their knowledge of planned wars and raids was very limited at best. Normally a quick dispersal of their followers won victory.<br>
<br>
Fizzlethorpe knew what to expect from what he was about to suggest. He grinned from ear to ear and chuckled softly. &quot;Perhaps its time for us to ask the great ones below to, and let the followers become the leaders,&quot;.<br>
<br>
This prompted a monstrous outcry from the oher Gods. &quot;Mortals!?!?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Them leading us into battle?!?!!?&quot; Fizzlethorpe didnt look to see who had what objections for he knew he was right, and he knew that once they thought about it they would see it too. All to many times the Mortals of Antonica had turned to them for salvation and grace in the face of battle, and now it was time for them to make a call to the mortals for such things................<br>
<br>
<br>
